  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Letter Sent to Tang Ku, an Official
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Winter's chill descends. I humbly inquire after your esteemed well-being, yet cannot contain my longing gaze toward you. Our small nation's affairs remain unchanged from what I have thrice conveyed before. Since that day in the years of Gimyo and Sinmyo when we bowed in submission and achieved peace, we have found solace in reliance upon great powers. The whole realm rejoices—a blessing witnessed and confirmed by Heaven and Earth themselves.

    Yet what need have I for further words? The true condition of our humble nation today, you, the great official of the military command, have yourself beheld with your own eyes. Would you not take pity on this small realm?

    Fear and trembling still grip us; stability remains far from our grasp. I earnestly beseech you: before the imperial throne, speak truthfully of our plight. Let your words of weight and influence shield our small nation completely, that this grace might extend through ten thousand generations. How could such gratitude ever be adequately expressed?

    With utmost deference, I offer these humble local gifts, though unworthy to soil your honor. I can only hope you will graciously receive them.
  footnotes:
    - Gimyo (己卯) and Sinmyo (辛卯) refer to the years 1219 and 1231 respectively, marking Goryeo's submission to the Mongol Empire and the subsequent peace agreement.
    - The 'military command' (帥府) refers to the Mongol administrative structure governing Goryeo at this time.
